Rummage Sale

Atlantic Community School District will be holding a rummage sale, Saturday, November 2, 2019 from 8:00 am- 12:00 pm at both the Bus Garage (2805 E. 7th St.) and Achievement Center (1406 SW 7th St.) locations.

Items for sale will include: Miscellaneous Desks, Chairs, Tables, Ceiling fans, Heating/air conditioning units, 42 Gym Lights 400 w 277 volt, lunch tables and other miscellaneous items.

If you have any questions regarding any of these items please contact Russell Peck - ACSD Maintenance Director at 712-249-3041.

post_text:
Congratulations to

Hailee Plagmann - Daughter of Gary & Kathy Plagmann (this is Hailee's third year being accepted into this prestigious choir)
Dawsen Sorensen - Son of Stacie & Ronnie Schwaller and Chad Sorensen
Danielle Bennett - Daughter of Scott & Christine Bennett

on being accepted into the 2019 OPUS Honor Choirs.

Over 2,600 students were nominated by their directors for 720 positions in the four Opus Honor Choirs. Selections were made by means of a recorded audition.

The 2019 Opus Honor Choirs will perform at 4 pm Nov. 21 in C.Y. Stephens Auditorium in the Iowa State Center in Ames. The Opus Honor Choir Festival is made possible by the Iowa Choral Directors Association, Inc. Accepted singers are the students of Cheryl Thomson, Atlantic Middle School choir Director.

post_text:
3rd graders are learning how to upload their art projects onto Artsonia. They take a photo, edit the photo, and upload it onto the website. Artsonia is an online Art Gallery published by students and teachers.
Parents and family can view art online, leave comments, and order keepsakes featuring the artwork made by their child. 20% of the money spent on Artsonia is donated back to the classroom for new art supplies.
(If anyone has a child at Washington that doesnt have an account already set up, you will have the option to sign up at conferences in the art room)

post_text: Washingtons First Graders participated in their Annual Harvest Days. Each first grade class went to five different stations. Presentations included safety on the farm, farm animals, beef producers, dairy information, and farm machinery. They were treated to t-shirts and steak bites by the Beef Producers as well as learning about sheep, pigs, goats, and chickens with Jeff Anderson. Students were able to check out a combine from Lindemans and visit with local FFA students. Students interacted with presenters from Milk Unlimited and the Iowa State Extension Service and their Farm Safety models. What a great learning experience provided by our community and first graders!

Atlantic Police Department added 24 new photos to the album: 2017 "Pie in the Face".
January 31, 2018 at 11:13 AM 路

Today, Chief Erickson and Sheriff McLaren gladly took "pies to the face" as a way to say thank you to the students of Washington and Schuler Elementary schools. These schools participated in a "Canned Food Drive" that ran from November 27th-December 6th. During this food drive, Washington Elementary donated 3,520 and Schuler Elementary donated 2,471. This brought a grand total of 5,991 items donated to the local food pantry. In the five year history of the program, the two schools have helped donate 19,789 items to the Atlantic food pantry. We would once again like to say thank you to all of the students and their families who helped make this program such a success.

It was a great day of learning for the 6th graders and we appreciate Congressman Youngs visit!"

post_text: Also honored at the IASC (Iowa Association of Student Councils) Fall Leadership Conference last Monday was the Middle School Student Council. Ava Bruckner, Addie DeArment, and Reagan Leonard accepted the award on behalf of the Middle School Student Council. Again this year the council earned the highest honor given to student councils, "Honor Council with Meritorious Distinction". In order to obtain this award, the council must put together a portfolio of evidence of all the projects they did during the last school year. This is the 4th year in a roll that the council has earned this award.

post_text: "The Mobile Food Pantry was held last night Sept 6th from 430-630. We received 14,000 pounds of food from Foodbank of the Heartland out of Omaha Ne. Items ranged from frozen cherries - canned fruits and vegetables - bakery items - fresh sweetcorn - potatoes - cabbage and a variety of snacks. Each family walked away with at least 4-5 boxes of food. This would not be possible without the help of all the volunteers - including food service staff, student council, families, teachers, students and administration. We served over 156 families with approximately 685 individuals benefiting from this food. Our next mobile food pantry will be on Wednesday December 6th at the High school. Truck comes at 330 and we start distributing food at 430 or sooner if we get the tables set up. Everyone is welcome and there are no income guidelines."
